{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff408293-62a8-4c14-ae1c-c0b9c87cc32b","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in container), use `dotnet-trace` as a [global tool via single-file download](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#install) instead.\n- For production-safe collection with minimal overhead, prefer `cpu-sampling` over `cpu-tracing`.\n- If you suspect a CPU *spike*, use `--duration` or attach/detach interactively (press `Enter` to stop).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60b01242-8328-49b3-b50d-7649ddd7e74d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"9430:25127A:17D0F1C:1B1C185:69E81E51"},"id":"643d4dcd-f22c-456e-b227-da9e66ece946","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:23.804Z","parentId":"7f93ea44-6c58-41a7-b484-a79c213a9140"}
